### Lists and Keys

Use JavaScript's `map()` method to render lists of elements. Each item needs a unique `key` prop for React to track changes efficiently.

---

### Rendering Lists

```jsx
const items = ['Apple', 'Banana', 'Cherry'];
const listItems = items.map((item, index) => <li key={index}>{item}</li>);
return <ul>{listItems}</ul>;
```

### Keys

Keys help React identify which items changed, were added, or removed:

```jsx
function TodoList({ todos }) {
  return (
    <ul>
      {todos.map(todo => (
        <li key={todo.id}>
          {todo.text}
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

### Key Rules

| Rule | Reason |
|------|--------|
| Use stable IDs | Index can shift when items change order |
| Unique among siblings | Duplicate keys cause unpredictable behavior |
| Avoid using index | Use only as last resort for static lists |
| Keys are not passed as props | React uses keys internally |

### Filtering Lists

```jsx
const filtered = items.filter(item => item.active);
return filtered.map(item => <Item key={item.id} {...item} />);
```

> **Key Point:** A good key is a unique and stable identifier from your data (like a database ID). Using array index as key can cause bugs with dynamic lists.

codeExample:
function ProductList({ products }) {
  return (
    <div className="product-list">
      {products.map(product => (
        <ProductCard
          key={product.id}
          title={product.name}
          price={product.price}
        />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
